    <name>
      <text>Equations of Lines Parallel and Perpendicular to a Given Line</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Find the equation of the line that passes through the point \( ({@x_cor@},{@y_cor@}) \) and is</p>

<p>\( (a) \) parallel to the line {@par_line@}</p>
<p>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]</p>
<br>
<p>\( (b) \) perpendicular to the line {@perp_line@}</p>
<p>[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]</p>
<p></p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked solution</h3> 
<p>\( (a) \) By writing the linear equation \( {@par_line@} \) in slope-intercept form, \( \displaystyle {@eqn1a@} \), </p>
<p> you can see that the line has a slope: \(m=\displaystyle {@slope1_par@}\). </p>
<p>The line through the point \( ({@x_cor@},{@y_cor@}) \) that is parallel to the given line also has the same slope: \(\displaystyle {@slope1_par@}\).</p>
<p> The general equation form is \(y-y_1=m(x-x_1) \)</p>
<p> Substitute {@y_cor@} for \(y_1 \) and {@x_cor@} for \(x_1 \), we have </p>
<p>\({@y-y_cor@} = \displaystyle {@slope1_par@}({@x-x_cor@}) \)</p>
<p>\(y = \displaystyle {@expand(slope1_par*(x-x_cor))+y_cor@} \) </p>
<p>\( (b)\) By writing the equation {@perp_line@} in slope-intercept form, we can get a slope \( m_1\) of the line </p>
<p> and thus find  \( m_2\) of the perpendicular line, using the negative reciprocal of  \( m_1\).</p>
{@perp_line@} \( \implies  \displaystyle {@eqn1b@}\)
<p>Therefore, \( m_1 = \displaystyle {@slope2_perp@}\) and \( m_2= \displaystyle {@m_2@}\)</p>
<p>From there, using  \( m_2\), we can compute the equation of a line passing through \( ({@x_cor@},{@y_cor@}) \) </p><p>which is perpendicular to {@perp_line@} as asked in the question.  </p>
<p>\(y-y_1=m_{2}(x-x_1) \), </p>
<p>\({@y-y_cor@} = \displaystyle{@m_2@}({@x-x_cor@}) \)</p>
<p>\( y= \displaystyle {@expand(m_2*(x-x_cor))+y_cor@} \) </p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
